lines.value: <!==history== some sources suggest ferdinand verbiest whilst a member of a jesuit mission in china may have built the first steam powered car around 1672
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: francois isaac de rivaz a swiss inventor designed the first internal combustion engine which was fuelled by a mixture of hydrogen and oxygen and used it to develop the world's first vehicle to run on such an engine
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: the design was not very successful as was the case with samuel brown samuel morey and etienne lenoir who each produced vehicles powered by clumsy internal combustion engines
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: an automobile powered by an otto gasoline engine was built in germany by karl benz in 1885 and granted a patent in the following year
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: although several other engineers including gottlieb daimler wilhelm maybach and siegfried marcus were working on the problem at about the same time benz is generally credited with the invention of the modern automobile
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: approximately 25 of benz's vehicles were built before 1893 when his first four wheeler was introduced
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: they were powered with four stroke engines of his own design
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: emile roger of france already producing benz engines under license now added the benz automobile to his line of products
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: because france was more open to the early automobiles more were built and sold in france through roger than benz sold in germany
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: from 1890 to 1895 about 30 vehicles were built by daimler and his assistant maybach either at the daimler works or in the hotel hermann where they set up shop after falling out with their backers
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: benz and daimler seem to have been unaware of each other's early work and worked independently
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: in 1890 emile levassor and armand peugeot of france began producing vehicles with daimler engines and so laid the foundation of the motor industry in france
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: the first american car with a gasoline internal combustion engine supposedly was designed in 1877 by george selden of rochester new york who applied for a patent on an automobile in 1879
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: in britain there had been several attempts to build steam cars with varying degrees of success with thomas rickett even attempting a production run in 1860
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: santler from malvern is recognized by the veteran car club of great britain as having made the first petrol powered car in the country in 1894 followed by frederick william lanchester in 1895 but these were both one offs
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: the first production vehicles came from the daimler motor company founded by harry j lawson in 1896 and making their first cars in 1897
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: in 1892 rudolf diesel got a patent for a new rational combustion engine
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: in 1897 he built the first diesel engine
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: in 1895 selden was granted a united states patent( for a two stroke automobile engine which hinderd more than encouraged development of autos in the united states
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: steam electric and gasoline powered autos competed for decades with gasoline internal combustion engines achieving dominance in the 1910s
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: the large scale production line manufacturing of affordable automobiles was debuted by ransom olds at his oldsmobile factory in 1902
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: this assembly line concept was then greatly expanded by henry ford in the 1910s
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: development of automotive technology was rapid due in part to the hundreds of small manufacturers competing to gain the world's attention
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: key developments included electric ignition and the electric self starter both by charles kettering for the cadillac motor company in 1910-1911 independent suspension and four wheel brakes
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: although various pistonless rotary engine designs have attempted to compete with the conventional piston and crankshaft design only mazda's version of the wankel engine has had more than very limited success
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: since the 1920s nearly all cars have been mass produced to meet market needs so marketing plans have often heavily influenced automobile design
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: it was alfred p sloan who established the idea of different makes of cars produced by one company so buyers could move up as their fortunes improved
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: the makes shared parts with one another so larger production volume resulted in lower costs for each price range
lines.name: Buginese

lines.value: for example in the 1950s chevrolet shared hood doors roof and windows with pontiac the lasalle of the 1930s sold by cadillac used cheaper mechanical parts made by the oldsmobile division.-->
lines.name: Buginese
